[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Input and output operations on a computer can be extremely slow compared to the processing of data.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] An I/O device can incorporate mechanical devices that must physically move, such as a hard drive seeking a track to read or write; this is often orders of magnitude slower than the switching of electric current.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] For example, during a disk operation that takes ten milliseconds to perform, a processor that is clocked at one gigahertz could have performed ten million instruction-processing cycles.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] A simple approach to I/O would be to start the access and then wait for it to complete.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] But such an approach, called **synchronous I/O** or **blocking I/O**, would block the progress of a program while the communication is in progress, leaving system resources idle.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] When a program makes many I/O operations (such as a program mainly or largely dependent on user input), this means that the processor can spend almost all of its time idle waiting for I/O operations to complete.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Alternatively, it is possible to start the communication and then perform processing that does not require that the I/O be completed.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is called asynchronous input/output.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating system functions exist to implement asynchronous I/O at many levels.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] In fact, one of the main functions of all but the most rudimentary of operating systems is to perform at least some form of basic asynchronous I/O, though this may not be particularly apparent to the user or the programmer.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] In the simplest software solution, the hardware device status is polled at intervals to detect whether the device is ready for its next operation.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] (For example, the CP/M operating system was built this way.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Multitasking operating systems can exploit the functionality provided by hardware interrupts, whilst hiding the complexity of interrupt handling from the user.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Spooling was one of the first forms of multitasking designed to exploit asynchronous I/O.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Finally, multithreading and explicit asynchronous I/O APIs within user processes can exploit asynchronous I/O further, at the cost of extra software complexity.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Asynchronous I/O is used to improve energy efficiency, and in some cases throughput.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] However, it can have negative effects on latency and throughput in some cases.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] All forms of asynchronous I/O open applications up to potential resource conflicts and associated failure.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Careful programming (often using mutual exclusion, semaphores, etc.) is required to prevent this.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] When exposing asynchronous I/O to applications there are a few broad classes of implementation.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The form of the API provided to the application does not necessarily correspond with the mechanism actually provided by the operating system; emulations are possible.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Furthermore, more than one method may be used by a single application, depending on its needs and the desires of its programmer(s).
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Many operating systems provide more than one of these mechanisms, it is possible that some may provide all of them.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] In a multitasking operating system, processing can be distributed across different processes, which run independently, have their own memory, and process their own I/O flows; these flows are typically connected in pipelines.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Processes are fairly expensive to create and maintain, so this solution only works well if the set of processes is small and relatively stable.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] It also assumes that the individual processes can operate independently, apart from processing each other's I/O; if they need to communicate in other ways, coordinating them can become difficult.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] An extension of this approach is dataflow programming, which allows more complicated networks than just the chains that pipes support.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Polling provides non-blocking synchronous API which may be used to implement some asynchronous API.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Available in traditional Unix and Windows.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Its major problem is that it can waste CPU time polling repeatedly when there is nothing else for the issuing process to do, reducing the time available for other processes.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Also, because a polling application is essentially single-threaded it may be unable to fully exploit I/O parallelism that the hardware is capable of.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Available in BSD Unix, and almost anything else with a TCP/IP protocol stack that either utilizes or is modeled after the BSD implementation.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] A variation on the theme of polling, a select loop uses the `select` system call to sleep until a condition occurs on a file descriptor (e.g., when data is available for reading), a timeout occurs, or a signal is received (e.g., when a child process dies).
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] By examining the return parameters of the `select` call, the loop finds out which file descriptor has changed and executes the appropriate code.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Often, for ease of use, the select loop is implemented as an event loop, perhaps using callback functions; the situation lends itself particularly well to event-driven programming.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] While this method is reliable and relatively efficient, it depends heavily on the Unix paradigm that "everything is a file"; any blocking I/O that does not involve a file descriptor will block the process.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The select loop also relies on being able to involve all I/O in the central `select` call; libraries that conduct their own I/O are particularly problematic in this respect.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Some Unixes provide system-specific calls with better scaling; for example, `epoll` in Linux (that fills the return selection array with only those event sources on which an event has occurred), `kqueue` in FreeBSD, and event ports (and `/dev/poll`) in Solaris.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] SVR3 Unix provided the `poll` system call.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Arguably better-named than `select`, for the purposes of this discussion it is essentially the same thing.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] SVR4 Unixes (and thus POSIX) offer both calls.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] I/O is issued asynchronously, and when it is completed a signal (interrupt) is generated.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] As in low-level kernel programming, the facilities available for safe use within the signal handler are limited, and the main flow of the process could have been interrupted at nearly any point, resulting in inconsistent data structures as seen by the signal handler.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The signal handler is usually not able to issue further asynchronous I/O by itself.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The *signal* approach, though relatively simple to implement within the OS, brings to the application program the unwelcome baggage associated with writing an operating system's kernel interrupt system.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Its worst characteristic is that *every* blocking (synchronous) system call is potentially interruptible; the programmer must usually incorporate retry code at each call.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Available in the classic Mac OS, VMS and Windows.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *signal* method as it is fundamentally the same thing, though rarely recognized as such.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The difference is that each I/O request usually can have its own completion function, whereas the *signal* system has a single callback.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] On the other hand, a potential problem of using callbacks is that stack depth can grow unmanageably, as an extremely common thing to do when one I/O is finished is to schedule another.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] If this should be satisfied immediately, the first callback is not 'unwound' off the stack before the next one is invoked.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Systems to prevent this (like 'mid-ground' scheduling of new work) add complexity and reduce performance.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] In practice, however, this is generally not a problem because the new I/O will itself usually return as soon as the new I/O is started allowing the stack to be 'unwound'.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The problem can also be prevented by avoiding any further callbacks, by means of a queue, until the first callback returns.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Light-weight processes (LWPs) or threads are available in most modern operating systems.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Like the *process* method, but with lower overhead and without the data isolation that hampers coordination of the flows.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Each LWP or thread itself uses traditional blocking synchronous I/O, which simplifies programming logic; this is a common paradigm used in many programming languages including Java and Rust.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Multithreading needs to use kernel-provided synchronization mechanisms and thread-safe libraries.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] This method is most suitable for extremely large-scale applications like web servers due to the large numbers of threads needed.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] This approach is also used in the Erlang programming language runtime system.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The Erlang virtual machine uses asynchronous I/O using a small pool of only a few threads or sometimes just one process, to handle I/O from up to millions of Erlang processes.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] I/O handling in each process is written mostly using blocking synchronous I/O.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] This way high performance of asynchronous I/O is merged with simplicity of normal I/O (cf. the Actor model).
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Many I/O problems in Erlang are mapped to message passing, which can be easily processed using built-in selective receive.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Fibers / Coroutines can be viewed as a similarly lightweight approach to do asynchronous I/O outside of the Erlang runtime system, although they do not provide exactly the same guarantees as Erlang processes.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Microsoft Windows, Solaris, AmigaOS, DNIX and Linux (using io_uring, available on 5.1 and above).
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] I/O requests are issued asynchronously, but notifications of completion are provided via a synchronizing queue mechanism in the order they are completed.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Usually associated with a state-machine structuring of the main process (event-driven programming), which can bear little resemblance to a process that does not use asynchronous I/O or that uses one of the other forms, hampering code reuse.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Does not require additional special synchronization mechanisms or thread-safe libraries, nor are the textual (code) and time (event) flows separated.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Available in VMS and AmigaOS (often used in conjunction with a completion port).
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Bears many of the characteristics of the *completion queue* method, as it is essentially a completion queue of depth one.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] To simulate the effect of queue 'depth', an additional event flag is required for each potential unprocessed (but completed) event, or event information can be lost.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Waiting for the next available event in such a clump requires synchronizing mechanisms that may not scale well to larger numbers of potentially parallel events.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Available in mainframes by IBM, Groupe Bull, and Unisys.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Channel I/O is designed to maximize CPU utilization and throughput by offloading most I/O onto a coprocessor.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The coprocessor has onboard DMA, handles device interrupts, is controlled by the main CPU, and only interrupts the main CPU when it's truly necessary.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] This architecture also supports so-called channel programs that run on the channel processor to do heavy lifting for I/O activities and protocols.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Available in Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Optimized for applications that process large numbers of small messages to achieve higher I/O operations per second with reduced jitter and latency.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The vast majority of general-purpose computing hardware relies entirely upon two methods of implementing asynchronous I/O: polling and interrupts.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Usually both methods are used together, the balance depends heavily upon the design of the hardware and its required performance characteristics.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Pure polling systems are entirely possible, small microcontrollers (such as systems using the PIC microcontroller) are often built this way.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] CP/M systems could also be built this way (though rarely were), with or without DMA.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Also, when the utmost performance is necessary for only a *few* tasks, at the expense of any other potential tasks, polling may also be appropriate as the overhead of taking interrupts may be unwelcome.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Most general-purpose computing systems rely heavily upon interrupts.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] A pure interrupt system may be possible, though usually some component of polling is also required, as it is very common for multiple potential sources of interrupts to share a common interrupt signal line, in which case polling is used within the device driver to resolve the actual source.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] (This resolution time also contributes to an interrupt system's performance penalty.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Over the years a great deal of work has been done to try to minimize the overhead associated with servicing an interrupt.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Hybrid approaches are also possible, wherein an interrupt can trigger the beginning of some burst of asynchronous I/O, and polling is used within the burst itself.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] This technique is common in high-speed device drivers, such as network or disk, where the time lost in returning to the pre-interrupt task is greater than the time until the next required servicing.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] (Common I/O hardware in use these days relies heavily upon DMA and large data buffers to make up for a relatively poorly-performing interrupt system.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] These characteristically use polling inside the driver loops, and can exhibit tremendous throughput.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] At one time this sort of hybrid approach was common in disk and network drivers where there was not DMA or significant buffering available.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] (In effect using the processor itself as a DMA engine.) The 6502 processor offered an unusual means to provide a three-element per-datum loop, as it had a hardware pin that, when asserted, would cause the processor's Overflow bit to be set directly.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Using only these two tools (polling, and interrupts), all the other forms of asynchronous I/O discussed above may be (and in fact, are) synthesized.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] In an environment such as a Java virtual machine (JVM), asynchronous I/O can be synthesized *even though* the environment the JVM is running in may not offer it at all.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] This is due to the interpreted nature of the JVM.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The JVM may poll (or take an interrupt) periodically to institute an internal flow of control change, effecting the appearance of multiple simultaneous processes, at least some of which presumably exist in order to perform asynchronous I/O.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] That, in fact, is the problem with using polling in any form to synthesize a different form of asynchronous I/O.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is a poll is wasted, and lost to overhead rather than accomplishing a desired task.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Every CPU cycle that is *not* a poll represents an increase in latency of reaction to pending I/O.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Striking an acceptable balance between these two opposing forces is difficult.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The trick to maximize efficiency is to minimize the amount of work that has to be done upon reception of an interrupt in order to awaken the appropriate application.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Secondarily (but perhaps no less important) is the method the application itself uses to determine what it needs to do.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Particularly problematic (for application efficiency) are the exposed polling methods, including the select/poll mechanisms.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Though the underlying I/O events they are interested in are in all likelihood interrupt-driven, the interaction *to* this mechanism is polled and can consume a large amount of time in the poll.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] This is particularly true of the potentially large-scale polling possible through select (and poll).
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] Interrupts map very well to Signals, Callback functions, Completion Queues, and Event flags, such systems can be very efficient.
[src:netty-java-lib/asynchronous-i-o] The following examples show three approaches to reading I/O.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:netty-java-lib/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
