[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] A **network socket** is a software structure within a network node of a computer network that serves as an endpoint for sending and receiving data across the network.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The structure and properties of a socket are defined by an application programming interface (API) for the networking architecture.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Sockets are created only during the lifetime of a process of an application running in the node.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Because of the standardization of the TCP/IP protocols in the development of the Internet, the term *network socket* is most commonly used in the context of the Internet protocol suite, and is therefore often also referred to as **Internet socket**.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In this context, a socket is externally identified to other hosts by its **socket address**, which is the triad of transport protocol, IP address, and port number.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The term *socket* is also used for the software endpoint of node-internal inter-process communication (IPC), which often uses the same API as a network socket.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The use of the term *socket* in software is analogous to the function of an electrical female connector, a device in hardware for communication between nodes interconnected with an electrical cable.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Similarly, the term *port* refers to external physical endpoints at a node or device.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) for the network protocol stack creates a handle for each socket created by an application, commonly referred to as a *socket descriptor*.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In Unix-like operating systems, this descriptor is a type of file descriptor.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] It is stored by the application process for use with every read and write operation on the communication channel.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] At the time of creation with the API, a network socket is bound to the combination of a type of network protocol to be used for transmissions, a network address of the host, and a port number.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Ports are numbered resources that represent another type of software structure of the node.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] They are used as service types, and, once created by a process, serve as an externally (from the network) addressable location component, so that other hosts may establish connections.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Network sockets may be dedicated for persistent connections for communication between two nodes, or they may participate in connectionless and multicast communications.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In practice, due to the proliferation of the TCP/IP protocols in use on the Internet, the term *network socket* usually refers to use with the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] It is therefore often also called **Internet socket**.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] An application can communicate with a remote process by exchanging data with TCP/IP by knowing the combination of protocol type, IP address, and port number.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] This combination is often known as a *socket address*.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] It is the network-facing access handle to the network socket.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The remote process establishes a network socket in its own instance of the protocol stack and uses the networking API to connect to the application, presenting its own socket address for use by the application.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] A protocol stack, usually provided by the operating system (rather than as a separate library, for instance), is a set of services that allows processes to communicate over a network using the protocols that the stack implements.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The operating system forwards the payload of incoming IP packets to the corresponding application by extracting the socket address information from the IP and transport protocol headers and stripping the headers from the application data.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) that programs use to communicate with the protocol stack, using network sockets, is called a **socket API**.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Development of application programs that utilize this API is called *socket programming* or *network programming*.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Internet socket APIs are usually based on the Berkeley sockets standard.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In the Berkeley sockets standard, sockets are a form of file descriptor, due to the Unix philosophy that "everything is a file", and the analogies between sockets and files.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Both have functions to read, write, open, and close.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In practice, the differences strain the analogy, and different interfaces (send and receive) are used on a socket.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In inter-process communication, each end generally has its own socket.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In the standard Internet protocols TCP and UDP, a socket address is the combination of an IP address and a port number, much like one end of a telephone connection is the combination of a phone number and a particular extension.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Sockets need not have a source address, for example, for only sending data, but if a program *binds* a socket to a source address, the socket can be used to receive data sent to that address.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Based on this address, Internet sockets deliver incoming data packets to the appropriate application process.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The distinctions between a socket (internal representation), socket descriptor (abstract identifier), and socket address (public address) are subtle, and these are not always distinguished in everyday usage.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Further, specific definitions of a *socket* differ between authors.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In IETF Request for Comments, Internet Standards, in many textbooks, as well as in this article, the term *socket* refers to an entity that is uniquely identified by the socket number.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In other textbooks, the term *socket* refers to a local socket address, i.e., a "combination of an IP address and a port number".
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In the original definition of *socket* given in RFC 147, as it was related to the ARPA network in 1971, *"the socket is specified as a 32-bit number with even sockets identifying receiving sockets and odd sockets identifying sending sockets."* Today, however, socket communications are bidirectional.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Within the operating system and the application that created a socket, a socket is referred to by a unique integer value called a *socket descriptor*.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] On Unix-like operating systems and Microsoft Windows, the command-line tools netstat or ss are used to list established sockets and related information.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] This example in Java, modeled according to the Berkeley socket interface, sends the string "Hello, world!" via TCP to port `80` of the host with address `203.0.113.0`.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Each packet sent or received on a datagram socket is individually addressed and routed.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Order and reliability are not guaranteed with datagram sockets, so multiple packets sent from one machine or process to another may arrive in any order or might not arrive at all.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In order to receive broadcast packets, a datagram socket should not be bound to a specific address, though in some implementations, broadcast packets may also be received when a datagram socket is bound to a specific address.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] and unique flow of error-free data without record boundaries, with well-defined mechanisms for creating and destroying connections and reporting errors.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] On the Internet, stream sockets are typically implemented using TCP so that applications can run across any network using TCP/IP protocol.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Allow direct sending and receiving of IP packets without any protocol-specific transport layer formatting.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] according to the chosen transport layer protocol (e.g.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] When reading from a raw socket, the headers are usually included.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] When transmitting packets from a raw socket, the automatic addition of a header is optional.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] (APIs), for example, those based on Berkeley sockets, support raw sockets.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] interface, but three years later, Microsoft limited Winsock's raw socket support because of security concerns.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Other socket types are implemented over other transport protocols, such as Systems Network Architecture and Unix domain sockets for internal inter-process communication.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Computer processes that provide application services are referred to as servers, and create sockets on startup that are in the *listening state*.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] These sockets are waiting for initiatives from client programs.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] A TCP server may serve several clients concurrently by creating a unique dedicated socket for each client connection in a new child process or processing thread for each client.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] These are in the *established state* when a socket-to-socket virtual connection or virtual circuit (VC), also known as a TCP session, is established with the remote socket, providing a duplex byte stream.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] A server may create several concurrently established TCP sockets with the same local port number and local IP address, each mapped to its own server-child process, serving its own client process.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] They are treated as different sockets by the operating system since the remote socket address (the client IP address or port number) is different; i.e., since they have different socket pair tuples.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] UDP sockets do not have an *established state*, because the protocol is connectionless.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] A UDP server process handles incoming datagrams from all remote clients sequentially through the same socket.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] UDP sockets are not identified by the remote address, but only by the local address, although each message has an associated remote address that can be retrieved from each datagram with the networking application programming interface (API).
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Local and remote sockets communicating over TCP are called **socket pairs**.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Each socket pair is described by a unique 4-tuple consisting of source and destination IP addresses and port numbers, i.e. of local and remote socket addresses.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] As discussed above, in the TCP case, a socket pair is associated on each end of the connection with a unique 4-tuple.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The term *socket* dates to the publication of RFC 147 in 1971, when it was used in the ARPANET.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Most modern implementations of sockets are based on Berkeley sockets (1983), and other stacks such as Winsock (1991).
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The Berkeley sockets API in the Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) originated with the 4.2BSD Unix operating system as an API.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Only in 1989, however, could UC Berkeley release versions of its operating system and networking library free from the licensing constraints of AT&T's copyright-protected Unix.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] 1987, AT&T introduced the STREAMS-based Transport Layer Interface (TLI) in UNIX System V Release 3 (SVR3). and continued into Release 4 (SVR4).
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Other early implementations were written for TOPS-20, MVS, VM, IBM-DOS (PCIP).
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] The socket is primarily a concept used in the transport layer of the Internet protocol suite or session layer of the OSI model.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Networking equipment such as routers, which operate at the internet layer, and switches, which operate at the link layer, do not require implementations of the transport layer.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] However, stateful network firewalls, network address translators, and proxy servers keep track of active socket pairs.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] In multilayer switches and quality of service (QoS) support in routers, packet flows may be identified by extracting information about the socket pairs.
[src:netty-java-lib/network-socket] Raw sockets are typically available in network equipment and are used for routing protocols such as IGRP and OSPF, and for Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] In computer science, an algorithm is called **non-blocking** if failure or suspension of any thread cannot cause failure or suspension of another thread; for some operations, these algorithms provide a useful alternative to traditional blocking implementations.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] A non-blocking algorithm is **lock-free** if there is guaranteed system-wide progress, and **wait-free** if there is also guaranteed per-thread progress.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] "Non-blocking" was used as a synonym for "lock-free" in the literature until the introduction of obstruction-freedom in 2003.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] The word "non-blocking" was traditionally used to describe telecommunications networks that could route a connection through a set of relays "without having to re-arrange existing calls" (see Clos network).
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Also, if the telephone exchange "is not defective, it can always make the connection" (see nonblocking minimal spanning switch).
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] The traditional approach to multi-threaded programming is to use locks to synchronize access to shared resources.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Synchronization primitives such as mutexes, semaphores, and critical sections are all mechanisms by which a programmer can ensure that certain sections of code do not execute concurrently, if doing so could corrupt shared memory structures.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] If one thread attempts to acquire a lock that is already held by another thread, the thread will block until the lock is free.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Blocking a thread can be undesirable for many reasons.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] An obvious reason is that while the thread is blocked, it cannot accomplish anything: if the blocked thread had been performing a high-priority or real-time task, it would be highly undesirable to halt its progress.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] For example, certain interactions between locks can lead to error conditions such as deadlock, livelock, and priority inversion.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Using locks also involves a trade-off between coarse-grained locking, which can significantly reduce opportunities for parallelism, and fine-grained locking, which requires more careful design, increases locking overhead and is more prone to bugs.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Unlike blocking algorithms, non-blocking algorithms do not suffer from these downsides, and in addition are safe for use in interrupt handlers: even though the preempted thread cannot be resumed, progress is still possible without it.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] In contrast, global data structures protected by mutual exclusion cannot safely be accessed in an interrupt handler, as the preempted thread may be the one holding the lock.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] While this can be rectified by masking interrupt requests during the critical section, this requires the code in the critical section to have bounded (and preferably short) running time, or excessive interrupt latency may be observed.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] A lock-free data structure can be used to improve performance.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] A lock-free data structure increases the amount of time spent in parallel execution rather than serial execution, improving performance on a multi-core processor, because access to the shared data structure does not need to be serialized to stay coherent.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] With few exceptions, non-blocking algorithms use atomic read-modify-write primitives that the hardware must provide, the most notable of which is compare and swap (CAS).
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Critical sections are almost always implemented using standard interfaces over these primitives (in the general case, critical sections will be blocking, even when implemented with these primitives).
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] In the 1990s all non-blocking algorithms had to be written "natively" with the underlying primitives to achieve acceptable performance.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] However, the emerging field of software transactional memory promises standard abstractions for writing efficient non-blocking code.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Much research has also been done in providing basic data structures such as stacks, queues, sets, and hash tables.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] These allow programs to easily exchange data between threads asynchronously.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Additionally, some non-blocking data structures are weak enough to be implemented without special atomic primitives.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Several libraries internally use lock-free techniques, but it is difficult to write lock-free code that is correct.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Non-blocking algorithms generally involve a series of read, read-modify-write, and write instructions in a carefully designed order.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Optimizing compilers can aggressively re-arrange operations.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Even when they don't, many modern CPUs often re-arrange such operations (they have a "weak consistency model"), unless a memory barrier is used to tell the CPU not to reorder.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] C++11 programmers can use `std::atomic` in `<atomic>`, and C11 programmers can use `<stdatomic.h>`, both of which supply types and functions that tell the compiler not to re-arrange such instructions, and to insert the appropriate memory barriers.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Wait-freedom is the strongest non-blocking guarantee of progress, combining guaranteed system-wide throughput with starvation-freedom.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is wait-free if every operation has a bound on the number of steps the algorithm will take before the operation completes.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] This property is critical for real-time systems and is always nice to have as long as the performance cost is not too high.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] It was shown in the 1980s that all algorithms can be implemented wait-free, and many transformations from serial code, called *universal constructions*, have been demonstrated.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] However, the resulting performance does not in general match even naïve blocking designs.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Several papers have since improved the performance of universal constructions, but still, their performance is far below blocking designs.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Several papers have investigated the difficulty of creating wait-free algorithms.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] For example, it has been shown that the widely available atomic *conditional* primitives, CAS and LL/SC, cannot provide starvation-free implementations of many common data structures without memory costs growing linearly in the number of threads.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] However, these lower bounds do not present a real barrier in practice, as spending a cache line or exclusive reservation granule (up to 2 KB on ARM) of store per thread in the shared memory is not considered too costly for practical systems.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Typically, the amount of store logically required is a word, but physically CAS operations on the same cache line will collide, and LL/SC operations in the same exclusive reservation granule will collide, so the amount of store physically required is greater.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Wait-free algorithms were rare until 2011, both in research and in practice.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] However, in 2011 Kogan and Petrank presented a wait-free queue building on the CAS primitive, generally available on common hardware.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Their construction expanded the lock-free queue of Michael and Scott, which is an efficient queue often used in practice.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] A follow-up paper by Kogan and Petrank provided a method for making wait-free algorithms fast and used this method to make the wait-free queue practically as fast as its lock-free counterpart.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] A subsequent paper by Timnat and Petrank provided an automatic mechanism for generating wait-free data structures from lock-free ones.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Thus, wait-free implementations are now available for many data-structures.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Under reasonable assumptions, Alistarh, Censor-Hillel, and Shavit showed that lock-free algorithms are practically wait-free.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Thus, in the absence of hard deadlines, wait-free algorithms may not be worth the additional complexity that they introduce.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Lock-freedom allows individual threads to starve but guarantees system-wide throughput.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is lock-free if, when the program threads are run for a sufficiently long time, at least one of the threads makes progress (for some sensible definition of progress).
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] In particular, if one thread is suspended, then a lock-free algorithm guarantees that the remaining threads can still make progress.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Hence, if two threads can contend for the same mutex lock or spinlock, then the algorithm is *not* lock-free.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is lock-free if infinitely often operation by some processors will succeed in a finite number of steps.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] For instance, if *N* processors are trying to execute an operation, some of the *N* processes will succeed in finishing the operation in a finite number of steps and others might fail and retry on failure.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] The difference between wait-free and lock-free is that wait-free operation by each process is guaranteed to succeed in a finite number of steps, regardless of the other processors.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] In general, a lock-free algorithm can run in four phases: completing one's own operation, assisting an obstructing operation, aborting an obstructing operation, and waiting.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Completing one's own operation is complicated by the possibility of concurrent assistance and abortion, but is invariably the fastest path to completion.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] The decision about when to assist, abort or wait when an obstruction is met is the responsibility of a *contention manager*.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] This may be very simple (assist higher priority operations, abort lower priority ones), or may be more optimized to achieve better throughput, or lower the latency of prioritized operations.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Correct concurrent assistance is typically the most complex part of a lock-free algorithm, and often very costly to execute: not only does the assisting thread slow down, but thanks to the mechanics of shared memory, the thread being assisted will be slowed, too, if it is still running.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Obstruction-freedom is the weakest natural non-blocking progress guarantee.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is obstruction-free if at any point, a single thread executed in isolation (i.e., with all obstructing threads suspended) for a bounded number of steps will complete its operation.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] All lock-free algorithms are obstruction-free.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Obstruction-freedom demands only that any partially completed operation can be aborted and the changes made rolled back.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Dropping concurrent assistance can often result in much simpler algorithms that are easier to validate.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Preventing the system from continually live-locking is the task of a contention manager.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Some obstruction-free algorithms use a pair of "consistency markers" in the data structure.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Processes reading the data structure first read one consistency marker, then read the relevant data into an internal buffer, then read the other marker, and then compare the markers.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] The data is consistent if the two markers are identical.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] Markers may be non-identical when the read is interrupted by another process updating the data structure.
[src:netty-java-lib/non-blocking-algorithm] In such a case, the process discards the data in the internal buffer and tries again.
